/-!
G-06 law-equation realization layer.

This file adds the reviewed input-vocabulary extension approved for G-06: laws
are realized as equations.  A `SemanticLawEquationWitnessIdealCore` carries a
ring-valued observable presheaf on the AAT site together with atom-indexed
violation-witness coordinates for each law index, and the coordinate family is
restriction-compatible.  The law witness ideal of each law is the span of its
atom-indexed violation coordinates, mirroring III.定義5.2, and the local
obstruction ideal is the III.定義6.1 selected sum reused verbatim from
`Formal.AG.LawAlgebra.ObstructionIdeal`.

The obstruction coefficient object is then *generated* as the ideal-quotient
presheaf `Observable / I_Ob`.  Its restriction maps are induced by
`Ideal.quotientMap` along the LawAlgebra `RestrictionCompatible` theorem, so
additive restriction functoriality is constructed, not supplied.

On this generated coefficient realization, the support-only `interpret` map is
no longer a free field: it is the obstruction-quotient class of an explicit
defect observable.  The law-as-equation semantic tie says only that a required
law holding on the displayed local reading places that reading's defect inside
the law's own atom-generated witness ideal.  The tie is pointwise and
chart-local: it contains no overlap equality, no `arrowCompatibilityLaw`, no
`sourceC0CechZero`, no residual-zero, and no `H1` zero.  The cross-chart
restriction equality demanded by G-06 is *derived* from the quotient
realization: lawful defects vanish in the quotient, and the zero section is a
common base-restriction realization, which routes through the Cycle 346 and
Cycle 311 theorems to the displayed required-law restriction evaluator and the
generated-Cech `sourceC0CechZero`.

The Cycle 347 no-go boundary is untouched: nothing here constructs a
base-restriction source for an arbitrary support-only source.  The positive
construction fires only for sources whose interpretation is generated by the
law-equation realization itself.
-/

noncomputable section

